comment: To be honest I cried it's been such a long time since I cried. Gosh I've been such a poop nugget to myself most of my life. Being on strict diets hating my body jerking my self around in life. Yoga Revolution is exactly what I needed to remind myself that some days I'm going to fall, I'm not always going to be on my A game and that's okay. It's just day 8 and I already fell like 6 times and each time it was amazing because each time I found the strength to try again instead of just getting angry at myself for not being able to hit a certain shape. Damn girl Adriene you changed my life.
Day 8 saved me from giving up and losing hope. Adriene I wish you nothing but the purest form of love because you saved me.

Finally doing this Revolution challenge now, and this Serenity practice was JUST what I needed. A very special THANK YOUUUU for the reminder during the bridge "if you have a couch pillow under your head, move it for now"--as soon as I did and focused on my upper back and neck muscles to roll...OMG THOSE AREAS HAD SO MUCH TENSION and I inadvertently became my own chiropractor. Amazing bonus!

I'm 61, and started yoga three years ago while taking care of my mother in her last years. I always wondered what yoga was about...thought it was a cult thing. Those three years with Adriene: Beginners, True, Home, and since then Dedicate and now Revolution, have literally saved my life...my physical self, spiritual self, and my practical and tactical self. I am becoming so rounded inside and out, and love FIND WHAT FEELS GOOD. Never have I thought I would hurt myself because of that simple phrase. And, I am so strong inside and out! Thank you, Adriene, as well as all of you. The support is overwhelming! I am grateful.

I just wanted to say that I have wanted to try Yoga for nearly a decade, but I didn't have the money or time regularity to join a class to actually get into the practice. I also get self conscious in group work out classes. Someone told me to check out YouTube. So I bought a Yoga mat one day, and did some free Yoga research online and your page came up. I figured I would give it a try and started with this Revolution segment. I have always been very interested in Indian culture and history as well as the interesting ideas of energy reading and chakras. I am so happy that I chose your video segments to watch and learn how to do the practice of Yoga. Over the last years i've attended several classes, hoping to understand why yoga is important and why so many people attest to its power. I was largely disenchanted by the yoga community's polarities. On one extreme, fitness and beauty gurus pushing the perverse ideals of physical beauty and weight loss in western society, and on the other,   the strict spiritual doctrines and mysticism of various yogis. Adriene is the first yoga instructor i've encountered who strikes a perfect balance between the two extremes, grounding the spiritual in the physical and the physical in the spiritual in a forgiving and lighthearted way. Now, not only do I see that yoga is important, but FEEL that it is essential to my body.

Also about reflexology, I'm a cosmetologist myself so I know a bot about it. You should look into lymph and how it follows through the body. There are lots of lymph nodes in the feet, hands, and in the throat. The ones in the throat actually swell in you get sick. This is because lymph nodes filter out toxins. If you massage them it helps bring down the swelling. Lymph follows wherever blood isn't, but blood and lymph are both part of the circulatory system. Different parts of the feet are connected to different parts of the body, for example, the heels of the feet are connected to sexual sensation. Pretty cool right?

Thank you so much for this, Adriene! This is my first attempt (ever) at Yoga and I'm already noticing both mental changes and improved mobility. The Sockets in my shoulders do no longer snap when I do push-ups or perform similar movements. I'm so glad that I have discovered your channel and yoga at this time in my life. I'm fairly certain that a younger version of me instantly would have discarded Yoga due to pride. Perhaps the biggest achievement is that I now allowing myself to fail and still keep going, knowing that me falling short in the present doesn't mean that I will fall short in the future. I feel blessed that I through your work have found a way to improve flexibility and my the overall health, because for the longest time I have been embarrassed about my stiff joints and limited movement. And also.. Whenever I get confused, insecure or doubtful you somehow miraculously manage to address those exact matters only a couple of minutes later through encouragement, or simply by recognising the problems we beginners might have with the training. Those moments have been truly valuable to me. There are a lot of new sensations I have discovered by following your lessons. For example: This whole day have been really emotional to me. My thighs feel beat up and I've been on the verge of crying multiple times. It's been quite confusing to say the least. I know you mentioned that this could happen in the video, but could you give an explanation to why it does?  These lessons have so far also helped me be more present and loving towards myself. This Mindfulness I'm experience through your lessons is something I have experienced previously and also lost track of multiple times in my life. But I think that I finally have reached a level where I'm ready to start establishing routines that will help me stay on this right track and not fall back into my old self-destructive ways of thinking. I rambling now. However, the real reason for me writing is that I wonder how you suggest us to continue when these 31 days are over? I prefer to do the yoga in the morning when I wake up and quite frankly I prefer watching somebody instruct me what to do than making up my own exercises. Much love from Sweden.

Since Adrienne invited us to share reflexology tips, just wanted to add a few more about the feet. There are also great meridian points in between your toes (especially between big toe and second toe) and also massaging the outside of your big toe is good for pain release (as well as the fatty part of your palm where thumb meets the wrist). I'm not a reflexologist but my yoga teacher is also a massage therapist so she always passes on great tips about reflexology in class. Also, make sure to drink lots of water after massaging the points (to help with detox/energy release with chakras--water is always a good idea in general after yoga practices, especially after this one today since we were massaging reflex points). Thanks, Adrienne. Another wonderful and mindful practice today. Namaste and hugs from NorCal! :)

One way that I show love to myself is at the very end of my practice, after the video. While I am getting up, I roll to either side and put myself in a slightly modified HAINES position. Anyone who has been a lifeguard will know this. You put the arm that is on the ground straight out and rest your head on it. Both legs, or at least the top one, are bent for stability and balance, and your top arm is lightly resting on the ground. Taking this time in this pose helps me remember that I am getting up, but that I can take this love for myself into my day. It's just a nice step and stops myself from wrenching myself off the floor. Thanks for this day's practice, Adriene!

It's day 8! Ain't that great? :) ... seriously though, Adriene, if you're keen to learn about feet, also consider learning about footwear and the relationship between foot shape and shoe shape (especially sneakers, where high impact activities take place in). Not necessarily the 'fit' of the shoe, as a shoe can be the right size, but still angle your joints (of which the feet have many!) in ways that are not noticeable in the short term, but can be harmful in the long term... You could do a "Yoga for a night after high heels" (haha) for treatment and maybe do a blog or send out emails about healthy shoe choices for prevention : )
